{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478686"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:14:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17534"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17534"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.19,0.05,0.07,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10224"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10224"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56679"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2468"},{"type":"tags","id":"2469"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5944"},{"type":"tags","id":"9655"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent due to concerns about delayed motor development. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. He initially achieved head control at three months but has since lost this ability. He has difficulty rolling over and appears floppy when handled. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has generalised hypotonia, more pronounced proximally than distally. Deep tendon reflexes are absent. He has a bell-shaped chest and paradoxical breathing. His cognitive development and social interaction appear age-appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Genetic testing for SMN1 gene deletion","Muscle biopsy","Brain magnetic resonance imaging","Nerve conduction studies","Creatine kinase level"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with features suggestive of spinal muscular atrophy (SMA) type 1, including progressive proximal muscle weakness, hypotonia, and loss of previously achieved motor milestones. The presence of paradoxical breathing and a bell-shaped chest suggests involvement of respiratory muscles, which is characteristic of SMA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing for SMN1 gene deletion\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard diagnostic test for SMA. Approximately 95% of SMA cases are caused by homozygous deletion of the SMN1 gene. This non-invasive test should be performed first as it is highly sensitive and specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain magnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerns about central nervous system pathology. However, the pattern of weakness, preserved cognition, and normal social development make a central cause less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreatine kinase level\u003C/strong\u003E is typically normal or only mildly elevated in SMA. While it would be elevated in conditions like muscular dystrophy, the clinical presentation here is more consistent with a lower motor neuron disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E and electromyography can help confirm lower motor neuron involvement but are not the initial test of choice given the availability of genetic testing. These tests are also technically challenging and uncomfortable in infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is invasive and unnecessary when genetic testing is available. It may show neurogenic atrophy in SMA but should be reserved for cases where the diagnosis remains unclear after less invasive testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly diagnosis of SMA is crucial as new treatments (including gene therapy, antisense oligonucleotides, and small molecule drugs) are most effective when started early in the disease course, ideally before significant motor neuron loss has occurred.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spinal muscular atrophy (SMA) typically presents with proximal muscle weakness and hypotonia in infancy.","Genetic testing for SMN1 gene deletion is the diagnostic test of choice for SMA.","Early recognition and referral are critical as treatment outcomes are better when started before symptom onset."],"references":["National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke. Spinal muscular atrophy [Internet]. Bethesda (MD): National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke; [cited 2024 Dec 17]. Available from: https://www.ninds.nih.gov/health-information/disorders/spinal-muscular-atrophy"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56679"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17534"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56679"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:54:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:55:42+10:30"},"relationshi